content.description:
A nice warmup ladder for those days out on the Lake. 

  Begin on two obvious jugs about shoulder width apart and use pockets and blocks to climb the less than vertical face. 

  It's possible to topout through the shrubs, but a solid stand position just below the greenery facilitates a forward-facing dive back into the lake.
content.protection:
Water. 

  Protect ya neck! The slab to the right of the start flares out prominently when levels are low, so double-check your holds before committing to laybacks, etc.
content.location: Just to the right of Gettin' High.

content.description: Start on Nikki's Flake, but after pulling the crux and hitting the awesome right hand slot, go left and up for climbing that is a bit steeper than Nikki's Flake.
This climb follows a right leaning flake and then pockets up an overhung face on medium sized holds.
content.location: This route is located on the first overhang you come to after getting into the water for the Corral approach.

content.description: This route starts on a large layback flake (when the water is low to average height) then continues up on pockets and sloping edges up a vertical face.
content.location: On the left hand side of the Corral Wall, shortly after the wall goes from overhung to vertical.

content.description: This tall, right facing layback jug crack is a very impressive line. Don't fall from the top!
content.location: On the right side of the Corral Wall, where the color changes from consistently white, to black and brown streaks.

content.description:
Start on the right hand side of the Corral on a dark colored, slightly overhung and hueco'ed section, get up high on the wall, then traverse left for about 100 feet until the obvious topout on the left most side of the wall. 

  Once you get high, the rock quality is pretty good, but be sure to check for lose holds before committing.
A tall, fun wall from vertical to overhung with very deep water that is climbable even when water levels are very low.
